This is a nitpick, but whatever: toki yo tomare! = O | toki wo tomare = X | DIO says "toki yo tomare" because he's commanding time to stop. Use of "yo" in this context is a means of addressing someone, usually from a position of authority/superiority. You usually see kings use this to address someone ("person yo, blah blah blah"). Having DIO use "yo" plays into the massive ego he has and how he thinks so highly of himself that he feels he can address time as something that obeys his commands. This is contrast to Jotaro who says "toki wa tomaru", or "time has stopped". Instead of commanding time like DIO, Jotaro states that time has stopped as a matter of fact, which also compliments Jotaro's character.
